each girls the "ways women lead." The essays present a range of different practical and theoretical issues of leadership and development, including mother nurture, emulation of and divergence from core values, internalized oppression, self determination, representation of the physical self, guardianship/governance of the body, cooperative economics, activism, contentiousness with or differentiation from the mother, and negotiation of leadership across public and private spheres. Together, they make a compelling argument for the necessity of continuing to teach the cultural and gender-specific resistance to oppression that has been passed along the Motherline, and to adapt this Motherline tradition to the lives and needs of women and girls in the 21st century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican American mothers. 0aLeadership. 0aWomanism. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Leadership Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aDiggs, Rhunette C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDozier-Henry, Oare’, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, S. Alease, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, S. Alease, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlake, Ceara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGovan, Sandra Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Simona J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Lakesia D., econtributor.4ctb4ht